{"id":"1301.4570","submitter":"Hong-Jian He","authors":"Hong-Jian He, Zhong-Zhi Xianyu","title":"Spontaneous Spacetime Reduction and Unitary Weak Boson Scattering at the\n  LHC","comments":"Phys. Lett. B (in Press). arXiv admin note: text overlap with\n  arXiv:1112.1028","journal-ref":"Physics Letters B 720 (2013) 142-147","doi":"10.1016/j.physletb.2013.01.065","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph gr-qc hep-ex","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Theories of quantum gravity predict spacetime dimensions to become reduced at\nhigh energies, a striking phenomenon known as spontaneous dimensional reduction\n(SDR). We construct an effective electroweak theory based on the standard model\n(SM) and incorporate the TeV-scale SDR, which exhibits good high energy\nbehavior and ensures the unitarity of weak gauge boson scattering. This also\nprovides a natural solution to the hierarchy problem in the presence of scalar\nHiggs boson. We demonstrate that this model predicts unitary longitudinal weak\nboson scattering, and can be discriminated from the conventional 4d SM by the\nWW scattering experiments at the CERN LHC.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 19 Jan 2013 15:18:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-02-27"}
{"id":"1301.4987","submitter":"Fang-Yu Hong","authors":"Fang-Yu Hong, Huiqin Qian, Jing-Li Fu, Zhi-Yan Zhu, Li-zhen Jiang","title":"Strong Coupling between a Topological Qubit and a Nanomechanical\n  Resonator","comments":"5 pages, 3 figures. arXiv admin note: text overlap with\n  arXiv:1301.4537","journal-ref":"Physical Review A 87, 032339 (2013)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.87.032339","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We describe a scheme that enables a strong coherent coupling between a\ntopological qubit and the quantized motion of a magnetized nanomechanical\nresonator. This coupling is achieved by attaching an array of magnetic tips to\na namomechanical resonator under a quantum phase controller which coherently\ncontrols the energy gap of a topological qubit. Combined with single-qubit\nrotations the strong coupling enables arbitrary unitary transformations on the\nhybrid system of topological and mechanical qubits and may pave the way for the\nquantum information transfer between topological and optical qubits. Numerical\nsimulations show that quantum state transfer and entanglement distributing\nbetween the topological and mechanical qubits may be accomplished with high\nfidelity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 19 Jan 2013 08:02:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-12"}
{"id":"1301.4988","submitter":"Deepali Virmani","authors":"Deepali Virmani and Satbir Jain","title":"Centralized Lifetime Maximizing Tree For Wireless Sensor Networks","comments":"6 pages","journal-ref":"International Journal of Computer and Electrical Engineering vol.\n  1, no. 5,2009","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.NI","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  To enable data aggregation among the event sources in wireless sensor\nnetworks and to reduce the communication cost there is a need to establish a\ncoveraged tree structure inside any given event region to allow data reports to\nbe aggregated at a single processing point prior to transmission to the\nnetwork. In this paper we propose a novel technique to create one such tree\nwhich maximizes the lifetime of the event sources while they are constantly\ntransmitting for data aggregation. We use the term Centralized Lifetime\nMaximizing Tree (CLMT) to denote this tree. CLMT features with identification\nof bottleneck node among the given set of nodes. This node collects the data\nfrom every other node via routes with the highest branch energy subject to\ncondition loop is not created. By constructing tree in such a way, protocol is\nable to reduce the frequency of tree reconstruction, minimize the delay and\nmaximize the functional lifetime of source nodes by minimizing the additional\nenergy involved in tree reconstruction.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 19 Jan 2013 09:59:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-01-23"}
